<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Resolution (LAI 004)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Transforming Legal Aid</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This evidence sets out some of the issues raised by the proposed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">introduction of a residence test for legal aid claimants in children and family cases.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">About Resolution </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Resolution, which was formerly known as the Solicitors Family Law Association (SFLA), is an organisation of 6,500 members who believe in a constructive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, non‐confrontational approach to family law matters. Resolution also campaigns for improvements to the family justice system. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">For further information </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">please contact Rachel Rogers, Resolution’s Head of Policy: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">rachel.rogers@resolution.org.uk </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">/ 020 3195 01</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">89, or Matt Bryant, Director of Communications: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">matt.bryant@resolution.org.uk </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">/ 020 3195 0190.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Principle of a residence test </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As a matter of principle </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Resolution </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">do</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> not support this proposed policy change.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The meaning of residence in this context is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">undefined, so unclear and potentially legally complex.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is no data available to estimate the impact of the proposed policy on the number of those eligible for legal aid or costs.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Residence test in family cases</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There appears to be no justification </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for a residence test in family cases (where rules of jurisdiction already apply) which may involve domestic abuse, forced marriage, child abduction or state intervention in family life.  The Committee may wish to ask the government what they consider the j</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ustification to be.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The proposal effectively removes protection for sufferers of domestic abuse given priority for legal aid under the 2013 reforms.  A class of sufferers will be denied protection for themselves and their children due to their immigration</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> status, even if they have been here for some time.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is no evidence that this issue affects public confidence in family legal aid or that the current rules relating to jurisdiction are causing major difficulties.  In family law, the rules for jurisdi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ction derive from EU law and/or the Hague Convention(s) which deal with close connection within those rules.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It would be wrong in principle for parties, including child parties, in care proceedings to not be eligible for legal aid.  A parent would not hav</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e representation to oppose the removal of a child for the sole reason that the family does not necessarily have residence status, with potentially the local authority being the only legally represented party.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-indent:-17.85pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As well as prejudicing the parties, lack of re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">presentation is likely to impact on the timely conduct of the care proceedings.  It is unclear how some parents could be expected to provide evidence of residence in time for the crucial first hearing, or what the position of a children’s guardian with no </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ability to instruct a solicitor on behalf of the child would be.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In our response to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Transforming Legal Aid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> consultation we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">asked the government for confirmation that respondents to care proceedings (which are not excluded from the residence test) will</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> continue to be entitled to legal aid as now whatever their residence status - both those who are here unlawfully or beyond our borders - who are parents who can go on to take responsibility for looking after their children and maintain the children’s futu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">re within their family. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> We are hoping for specific details in the government’s response to the consultation responses when published.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To the extent that asylum seekers involved in public or private children proceedings will be reliant on fresh claims, th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is must create delay and risk especially where matters are urgent.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.2pt; padding-left:4.5pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">N</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">either of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">forced marriage victims </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">below </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">based on real life cases </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">would satisfy the residence test as proposed:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.75pt; padding-left:4.95pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A young woman forced to marry in Pakistan by her brothers. Her husband </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is severely disabled, yet physically strong, and with compulsion towards deeply degrading sexual practices and violence.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 53.7pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">If she goes back to Pakistan she will be killed for dishonouring her family by leaving the marriage. She has been in the UK for only t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hree months before she was assisted to flee her husband.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.26pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">recent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">marriage was forced on the husband, and the young woman was given no choice but to agree. The husband already has a white wife and children, and is her first cousin. She has been told she i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s not allowed to leave her in laws, who are also her family by birth. She is being treated as a domestic slave.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">concerned about the potential impact on child abduction cases where one parent lives outside the UK.  Although the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">government claim</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that legal aid will continue to be available where necessary to comply with EU or international law, we understand that at Ministry of Justice (MOJ) consultation events it has been communicated that the residence test will apply to child abduction cases </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ruling out many foreign claims for child abduction here.  The residence test should not apply to the left behind parent in Hague child abduction cases (who is almost always by definition not resident in the UK and probably never has been).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">3 September 2013</span></p></div></body></html>